q_co_cmnt: I think the directions can be simplified, which will help a bit.   /  / The spacing of the survey elements is also a little odd: not so much for the actual survey, but that first set of introductory pages. /  / The most difficult thing, though, is that the "please select all that apply" provision is sort of mentally confounding.  I might formulate it as either "does this palette match" or as "pick the palette that *most* matches."

q_comment: The directions are written in slightly broken English.  I recommend you have someone proof read it.  Also, I tried taking this survey one my phone and tablet but the word cloud did not display so all I could see were the color palette.  This could definitely affect your results because I was confused at first and thought we were just supposed to pick the most appealing palettes.
Sometimes it was hard to not just pick my favorite color pallet on the right.  It took some effort to go with the one that matched the word cloud versus going with my favorite set of colors.

I wonder if the survey takers are biased by their personal color preferences, rather than by society/culture.  If someone naturally prefers blue over red, they may not ever choose red as a color they associate with a given idea.  Regardless, this is an interesting survey, and it was kind of fun! I hope you are able to find some correlations with your data.
girl topics are every color of the rainbow / boy topics are grey
I woud like some yellow for the word cloud about parenting. /  / Also, you should say "any comments" not "any comment."

I am legally blind due to poor peripheral vision.  My straight ahead vision s not great, but is good enough that it does not qualify me for a status of legally blind.  Due to retina damage, I have very limited vision without significant light and contrast.
I'm pretty sure the survey was not working properly on the iPhone. The word clouds were not visible with the color palettes.

was a bit tiring, I was less attentive toward the end. I felt some clouds applied to all the palettes and I wasn't sure if this was okay. sounds like an interesting study, though, so I wanted to participate.

Blues and blacks remind me of business type stuff. Earthy tones such as brown and green for the garden or outdoors. More feminine colors such as pinks and purples for home, fashion or women. Fashion or interior decorating related palettes also should have more contrast and different colors other than 5 different shades of purple.
